Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) bridges the gap between object-oriented code and
relational databases.

Key components include:

 * Model: Defines the data structure.
 * Context: Acts as an in-memory database, allowing CRUD operations.
 * Mappings: Specifies relationships between classes and database tables.


WORKING OF THE ENTITY FRAMEWORK

 * Model First: Design the model, then generate the database.
 * Database First: Use an existing database to generate a model.
 * Code First: Define classes and relationships first, then generate a database.


CORE CONCEPTS OF EF

 * DbContext: Represents a session with the database.

 * Entity: An object that you map to a table or a view in the database.

 * DbSet<T>: Represents a table or a view.

 * Entity State: Describes the state of an entity in the context.

   * Added
   * Modified
   * Deleted
   * Detached
   * Unchanged

 * Query: Describes how data is retrieved through LINQ.


COORDINATION BETWEEN DATABASE AND OBJECTS

 * Change Tracking: Records modifications made to entity objects during their
   lifecycle.

 * Relationship Management: Manages relational data by using techniques like
   lazy loading, eager loading, and explicit loading.

 * Transaction Management: Handles unit of work operations within the database.

 * Caching: Maintains an in-memory state of entities for enhanced performance.


CODE EXAMPLE: ENTITY FRAMEWORK

Here is the Csharp code:

// Define the model
public class Customer {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Order> Orders { get; } = new List<Order>();
}

public class Order {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public decimal Amount { get; set; }
}

// Define the context
public class MyDbContext : DbContext {
    public DbSet<Customer> Customers { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Order> Orders { get; set; }
}

// Usage
using (var context = new MyDbContext()) {
    // Insert
    var customer = new Customer { Name = "John Doe" };
    context.Customers.Add(customer);

    // Query
    var customersWithOrders = context.Customers.Include(c => c.Orders).ToList();

    // Update
    customer.Name = "Jane Doe";

    // Remove
    context.Customers.Remove(customer);

    // Save changes
    context.SaveChanges();
}

DbContext, a key part of Entity Framework, functions as an intelligent bridge
between the application and the database. It encapsulates the database session
and acts as a hub where entities are tracked, changes are managed, and datasets
are queried and persisted.


SETUP AND BEST PRACTICES

 * Database Context: Establish a database connection and provide database
   operations.
 * Entity Sets: Represent tables, their records, and relationships.


KEY FEATURES

 * Change Tracking: Alerts on any modifications to entities.
 * Lazy Loading: On-demand loading of related entities.
 * Early Loading: Immediate retrieval of data, including related entities.


MANAGEMENT AND PERSISTENCE

 * Inserts
 * Updates
 * Deletions
 * Transactions: Ensures atomic operations, safeguarded by rollback mechanisms.


CONTEXT LIFECYCLE

 * Transient: New instances are used per request.
 * Scoped: Corresponds to a unit of work or an HTTP request.
 * Singleton: A single instance shared across the entire application.


CODE EXAMPLE: DBCONTEXT

Here is the C# code:

using System;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

public class Product {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

public class StoreContext : DbContext {
    public DbSet<Product> Products { get; set; }

    protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder) {
        optionsBuilder.UseSqlServer("connection string");
    }
}

// Context usage
public class Program {
    static void Main() {
        using (var context = new StoreContext()) {
            // New product
            var newProduct = new Product { Name = "Laptop" };
            context.Products.Add(newProduct);

            // Update existing product
            var existingProduct = context.Products.Find(1);
            if (existingProduct != null) {
                existingProduct.Name = "Desktop";
            }

            // Delete a product
            var productToDelete = context.Products.Find(2);
            if (productToDelete != null) {
                context.Products.Remove(productToDelete);
            }

            // Commit changes
            context.SaveChanges();
        }
    }
}

DbSet in Entity Framework acts as a gateway to relational databases, enabling
you to interact with database tables using object-oriented programming.


CORE FUNCTIONS

 1. Entity Tracking: DbSet monitors changes made to the entities during their
    lifespan. Modifications are categorized as Added, Deleted, or Updated, based
    on which Entity Framework controls how the changes are reflected in the
    database.

 2. LINQ Queries: You can harness the power of Language-Integrated Query (LINQ)
    to extract, manipulate, and in some cases, construct new model entities from
    database tables. DbSet acts as a LINQ query provider.

 3. CRUD Operations: DbSet provides straightforward methods to: insert new
    entities (Add), update their values (Update), remove them (Remove), retrieve
    entities by their primary key (Find), and also execute bulk operations such
    as deleting all entities from the table in memory (RemoveRange).

 4. Data Binding: It offers data binding capabilities, making it easier to
    integrate entities seamlessly with UI components in supported platforms like
    WPF and WinForms. This ensures that changes in UI maps back to the entities
    and vice versa, and these changes are tracked effortlessly by the DbSet.
    This aids in handling more extensive workflows with many entities and
    updates. However, Data Binding is not supported in the most recent versions
    of Entity Framework Core.


CODE EXAMPLE: WORKING WITH DBSET

Here is the C# code:

public class MyDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Employee> Employees { get; set; }
}

public static void Main()
{
    using (var context = new MyDbContext())
    {
        // Retrieve an employee by their unique identifier
        var employee = context.Employees.Find(1);

        // Update the title of the employee
        employee.Title = "Senior Engineer";

        // Mark the entity as Modified
        context.Employees.Update(employee);

        // Save changes to the database
        context.SaveChanges();

        // Delete an employee
        var employeeToDelete = context.Employees.Find(2);
        context.Employees.Remove(employeeToDelete);
        context.SaveChanges();

        // Query for a specific set of employees
        var engineeringEmployees = context.Employees.Where(e => e.Department == "Engineering").ToList();
    }
}

Lazy loading allows related objects to be fetched from the database only when
they are accessed. This reduces the initial data load, making the system more
efficient.


KEY COMPONENTS

 * Proxy Generation: When a navigation property is virtual, Entity Framework
   generates a dynamic proxy at runtime.

 * Interception Mechanism: Access to the navigation property triggers a database
   query through a proxy instance. The process is monitored by EF to maintain
   data consistency.

 * Underlying Context Connection: The context maintains a virtual link to
   related entities. Actual data fetching occurs once there's a navigation
   property access for the first time within a context session.


PERFORMANCE CONSIDERATIONS

While lazy loading can enhance efficiency, it may also introduce performance
overheads. If misused, it can result in the N+1 problem, where many additional
queries are executed, leading to performance degradation.

Also, when used in disconnected scenarios, such as within a web application,
late queries can cause unexpected issues.


CODE EXAMPLE: SALES CONTEXT

Here is the C# code:


public class SalesContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Order> Orders { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Customer> Customers { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Product> Products { get; set; }
}

public class Order
{
    public int OrderId { get; set; }
    public int CustomerId { get; set; }
    public virtual Customer Customer { get; set; }
    public virtual ICollection<Product> Products { get; set; }
}

public class Customer
{
    public int CustomerId { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public virtual ICollection<Order> Orders { get; set; }
}

public class Product
{
    public int ProductId { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
    public virtual ICollection<Order> Orders { get; set; }
}

While developing ASP.NET applications, you might need to switch between
different databases in an Entity Framework (EF) context.

Here are two common approaches to accomplish this:

 1. Code-based Selection: Perfect for instances where the choice of database is
    known at compile-time. You use an app.config or web.config to specify the
    database connection.

 2. Run-time Database Selection: Ideal for scenarios where the database to be
    used can only be determined at runtime.


CODE-BASED SELECTION

In environments where the database choice is known at compile-time, you can use
Conditional Compilation Directives to select the appropriate EF context, using
tools such as #if DEBUG to differentiate between, say, a development and a
production environment.

 * Code CSHarp

 #if DEBUG
     using (var db = new DevelopmentDbContext()) 
     {
        // Database logic for development environment
     }
 #else
     using (var db = new ProductionDbContext()) 
     {
        // Database logic for production environment
     }
 #endif



RUN-TIME DATABASE SELECTION

You can set the EF context at runtime, allowing the application to dynamically
switch between different databases based on user inputs or other factors. This
approach gives more flexibility and is often used in applications where the
database might change at runtime.

 * Code CSharp

  using System.Data.Entity;

  public class DbContextFactory
  {
      public DbContext GetDbContext(DatabaseType type)
      {
          switch(type)
          {
             case DatabaseType.Production:
                 return new ProductionDbContext();
             case DatabaseType.Staging:
                 return new StagingDbContext();
             default:
                 return new DevelopmentDbContext();
          }
      }
  }

  public enum DatabaseType
  {
      Production,
      Staging,
      Development
  }

  // Somewhere in your code...
  // var dbFactory = new DbContextFactory();
  // var db = dbFactory.GetDbContext(DatabaseType.Production);

Entity Framework simplifies CRUD actions by ensuring object-oriented domain
logic aligns with the data model. While these functions are readily accessible,
understanding the underlying mechanics is crucial for optimized performance.


KEY COMPONENTS

 1. DbContext: Acts as a bridge between the database and your domain models.
    It's the entry point for querying and saving data.

 2. DbSet: Represents a collection of entities where you can query and save
    entities.

 3. Entity: Corresponds to individual rows in the database, and any changes to
    the entity are tracked by EF.

 4. Change Tracker: Automatically monitors changes to entities during their
    lifespan.


CODE EXAMPLE: DEFINE MODELS

The code below demonstrates how to define DbContext, DbSet, and the entities:

 1. DbContext: CarRentalContext
 2. DbSet: Cars
 3. Entity: Car

Here is the C# code:

public class CarRentalContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Car> Cars { get; set; }
}

public class Car
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Make { get; set; }
    public string Model { get; set; }
}



PERFORMING CRUD OPERATIONS

 1. Create: Construct a new entity, attach it to the DbContext, and then save
    the changes.

 2. Read: Use DbContext to fetch entities either individually or as collections.

 3. Update: Modify the entity directly within the DbContext and then call
    SaveChanges.

 4. Delete: Either mark the entity as Deleted within the DbContext or use the
    Remove method before calling SaveChanges.

Here is the C# code:

// Create
using (var context = new CarRentalContext())
{
    var newCar = new Car { Make = "Honda", Model = "Accord" };
    context.Cars.Add(newCar);
    context.SaveChanges();
}

// Read
using (var context = new CarRentalContext())
{
    var specificCar = context.Cars.FirstOrDefault(c => c.Make == "Honda");
    var allCars = context.Cars.ToList();
}

// Update
using (var context = new CarRentalContext())
{
    var carToUpdate = context.Cars.FirstOrDefault(c => c.Make == "Honda");
    if (carToUpdate != null)
    {
        carToUpdate.Model = "Civic";
        context.SaveChanges();
    }
}

// Delete
using (var context = new CarRentalContext())
{
    var carToDelete = context.Cars.FirstOrDefault(c => c.Model == "Civic");
    if (carToDelete != null)
    {
        context.Cars.Remove(carToDelete);
        context.SaveChanges();
    }
}

Entity Framework (EF) supports bulk insert operations since EF version 6.1.
Below are some methods:

 * AddRange: This method accepts a collection of entities.

using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Data.Entity;

public class MyContext: DbContext
{
    public DbSet<EntityType> Table { get; set; }
}

public class EntityType
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        var context = new MyContext();
        var entities = GenerateEntities();
        context.Table.AddRange(entities);
        context.SaveChanges();
    }

    public static List<EntityType> GenerateEntities()
    {
        // Logic to create a list of entities - omitted for brevity
        return new List<EntityType>();
    }
}


 * SQL Bulk Copy: This method utilizes SqlBulkCopy to boost performance for
   large datasets.

 * Third-Party Libraries: You can also use libraries like EFUtilities,
   EntityFramework.Extended, or Z.EntityFramework.Extensions for more advanced
   bulk operations.

   However, be cautious as EF's change tracking and context are bypassed in
   these cases, which might lead to inconsistencies in certain scenarios.

Let's look at how to execute stored procedures using Entity Framework (EF), and
explore various scenarios.


CONFIGURATION METHODS

 1. Model-First Approach: GUI tools map stored procedures to entities.
 2. Code-First: Decorate methods with attributes or define mappings in the
    OnModelCreating method.


EXECUTING STORED PROCEDURES

RETURNING DATA

Code-First through DbContext:

using (var context = new YourDbContext())
{
    var resultList = context.Database.SqlQuery<YourEntityType>("StoredProcedureName @param1, @param2", 
        new SqlParameter("param1", val1), 
        new SqlParameter("param2", val2)).ToList();
}


 * DbContext: Exposes Database property containing SqlQuery for executing raw
   SQL and returning entities.

 * SqlQuery: Takes the stored procedure name and parameters, returning a
   collection of your entity type.

 * Query Types: Provision through code-first Func scenarios like object models
   and dynamic types. Keep models and types attached.

For Model-First Approach:

 * Configure your .edmx file. Complex Types map result sets, and Functions map
   stored procedures. Keep in mind this supports only EDMX models.

MODIFYING DATA

Code-First:

 1. Use ExecuteSqlCommand for single-statement procedures:

    using (var context = new YourDbContext())
    {
        context.Database.ExecuteSqlCommand("EXEC YourStoredProcedure @Param1", new SqlParameter("Param1", value));
    }


ExecuteSqlCommand: Runs SQL statements or scripts against the database.

 2. Work in a transaction for multi-statement procedures:

    using (var context = new YourDbContext())
    {
        using (var dbContextTransaction = context.Database.BeginTransaction()) {
            try {
                context.Database.ExecuteSqlCommand("MultiStatementStoredProcedure");
                dbContextTransaction.Commit();
            } catch (Exception) {
                dbContextTransaction.Rollback();
            }
        }
    }


BeginTransaction: Starts a database transaction.
Commit: Commits the database transaction.
Rollback: Rolls back the database transaction.


MANAGING DATA INTEGRITY

Ef throws exceptions on failure to execute stored procedures which results in
transactions. you can use DbContextTransaction class to manage a transaction
lifecycle and Dispose for cleaning the resources.

Keep in mind, multiple database providers might have slightly varying behavior
in EF Core.


CODE EXAMPLE: MODIFYING DATA WITH A STORED PROCEDURE

Here is the C# code:


using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using System;
using System.Data.SqlClient;

public class YourEntity
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

public class YourDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<YourEntity> YourEntities { get; set; }

    protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder options)
        => options.UseSqlServer("your-connection-string");

    public void RunStoredProcedureWithTransaction()
    {
        using (var context = new YourDbContext())
        {
            using (var dbContextTransaction = context.Database.BeginTransaction())
            {
                try
                {
                    context.Database.ExecuteSqlCommand("YourStoredProcedure @param1, @param2",
                        new SqlParameter("param1", "value1"),
                        new SqlParameter("param2", "value2")
                    );

                    dbContextTransaction.Commit();
                }
                catch (Exception ex)
                {
                    dbContextTransaction.Rollback();
                    throw ex;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

Entity Framework's transaction management offers a high-level of isolation and
control over database operations. EF ensures that operations are consistent and
that multiple operations are tracked within transaction boundaries, preventing
partial commit or loss of data integrity.


TRANSACTION LIFECYCLE

 1. Initialization:

    * Transactions are started either explicitly using BeginTransaction() or
      implicitly when an EF action is transactionally-sensitive (atomic
      operations, like SaveChanges).

 2. Operation Tracking:

    * During the transaction, EF monitors all operations associated with the
      involved entities.

 3. Completion:

    * Transactions can be committed to persist changes or rolled back to undo
      them.


CODE EXAMPLE: TRANSACTIONS IN EF

Here is the C# code:


var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<MyContext>()
    .UseSqlServer("connection-string")
    .Options;

using (var context = new MyContext(options))
{
    using (var transaction = context.Database.BeginTransaction())
    {
        try
        {
            // Perform multiple database operations inside the transaction.

            var student = new Student() {Name = "New Student"};
            context.Students.Add(student);

            var course = new Course() { Title = "New Course"};
            context.Courses.Add(course);

            context.SaveChanges();

            // If all operations are successful, commit the transaction.
            transaction.Commit();
        } 
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            // Any error in operations will cause a rollback of the entire transaction.
            transaction.Rollback();
        }
    }

    // Since our context is within a 'using' block, it will be disposed automatically.
}

Entity keys uniquely identify each record within a database table. In Entity
Framework (EF), they're essential for managing relationship integrity and for
various Orm features such as change tracking.


KEY TYPES

 * Primary Key (PK): Each entity must have a distinct PK. This is typically
   auto-generated and is set using the annotation [Key].

 * Foreign Key (FK): Points to a primary key in a related table, establishing a
   relationship.

 * Alternate Key: In addition to the primary key, entities can have one or more
   alternate keys for uniqueness, which is specified using the method
   .HasAlternateKey() in the code-first approach.


CONFIGURING KEYS IN CODE-FIRST APPROACH

Data Annotations:

public class Product {
    [Key]
    public int ProductId { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}


Fluent API:

public class MyContext : DbContext {
    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder) {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Product>()
            .HasKey(p => p.ProductId);
    }
}

In Entity Framework, you use relationships to link multiple entities in the
database. They are defined using navigation properties.


RELATIONSHIP TYPES

Entity Framework Core supports three primary relationship types:

 * One-to-One (1:1): Each entity instance is uniquely associated with a single
   corresponding instance in another entity.

 * One-to-Many (1: M): An instance in one entity can be related to multiple
   instances in another entity.

 * Many-to-Many (M: N): Entities on both ends can have multiple related entities
   from the other side. This relationship is achieved using a join entity.


DATA ANNOTATIONS FOR RELATIONSHIPS

ONE-TO-ONE

 * [InverseProperty("propertyName")]: Allows you to specify which navigation
   property represents the "other end" of a one-to-one relationship.

ONE-TO-MANY & MANY-TO-MANY

 * [ForeignKey("propertyName")]: Defines a foreign key property. It's necessary
   when the convention-based foreign key names are not followed or when using a
   shadow property.


EXAMPLE: DATA ANNOTATION

Here is the C# code:

using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations.Schema;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class Author
{
    public int AuthorId { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Book> Books { get; set; }
}

public class Book
{
    public int BookId { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }

    [ForeignKey("AuthorId")]
    public Author Author { get; set; }
}


In this example:

 * Author and Book have a one-to-many relationship (one Author can have many
   Books).
 * The [ForeignKey("AuthorId")] attribute links the AuthorId property in Book to
   the primary key AuthorId in Author.


FLUENT API FOR RELATIONSHIPS

The Fluent API uses a more methodical approach for relationship configurations.

 * Use fluent methods after the EntityTypeBuilder<TEntity> methods to define
   relationships.

EXAMPLE: FLUENT API

Here is the C# code:

using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

public class LibraryContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Author>()
            .HasMany(a => a.Books)
            .WithOne(b => b.Author)
            .HasForeignKey(b => b.AuthorId);

        base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);
    }
}


In this example:

 * We are using the HasMany, WithOne, and HasForeignKey methods to configure the
   one-to-many relationship between Author and Book.
 * This specific configuration is not achievable with data annotations,
   demonstrating the more fine-grained control you have with the Fluent API.

In Entity Framework, you can model different types of relationships between
entities:

 * One-to-Many: A child in one entity is related to multiple parents in another
   one
 * Many-to-Many: Both entities have a collection navigation property referring
   to the other


CODE EXAMPLE: ONE-TO-MANY RELATIONSHIP

Here is the C# code:

public class Author
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Book> Books { get; set; }
}

public class Book
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public int AuthorId { get; set; }
    public Author Author { get; set; }
}

public class LibraryContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }
}



FLUENT API EXAMPLE

protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    modelBuilder.Entity<Author>()
        .HasMany(a => a.Books)
        .WithOne(b => b.Author)
        .HasForeignKey(b => b.AuthorId);
}


Use the ICollection<T> (or List<T>) type for the "one" side, designating the end
of the relationship with multiple elements. The "many" side should have a
reference property.


CODE EXAMPLE: ONE-TO-ONE RELATIONSHIP

One-to-One relationships come in two flavors in EF: shared primary key and
unique foreign key. Let's look at the latter.

Here is the C# code:

public class Author
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public AuthorBiography Biography { get; set; }
}

public class AuthorBiography
{
    public int AuthorId { get; set; }
    public string Content { get; set; }
    public Author Author { get; set; }
}

public class LibraryContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
    public DbSet<AuthorBiography> AuthorBiographies { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Author>()
            .HasOne(a => a.Biography)
            .WithOne(b => b.Author)
            .HasForeignKey<AuthorBiography>(b => b.AuthorId);
    }
}


In this example, both the Author and AuthorBiography classes have a navigation
property pointing to the other class. The HasForeignKey method specifies the
foreign key explicitly.


CODE EXAMPLE: MANY-TO-MANY RELATIONSHIP

Here is C# code:

public class Student
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<StudentCourse> StudentCourses { get; set; }
}

public class Course
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public ICollection<StudentCourse> StudentCourses { get; set; }
}

public class StudentCourse
{
    public int StudentId { get; set; }
    public Student Student { get; set; }
    public int CourseId { get; set; }
    public Course Course { get; set; }
}

public class SchoolContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Student> Students { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Course> Courses { get; set; }
    public DbSet<StudentCourse> StudentCourses { get; set; }
}


Here, we introduce a dedicated join entity: StudentCourse, which maps students
to courses.

Group the relationships that form the many-to-many association in a single
navigation property. This ensures both directions are defined.


ONMODELCREATING

protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    modelBuilder.Entity<StudentCourse>()
        .HasKey(sc => new { sc.StudentId, sc.CourseId });

    modelBuilder.Entity<StudentCourse>()
        .HasOne(sc => sc.Student)
        .WithMany(s => s.StudentCourses)
        .HasForeignKey(sc => sc.StudentId);

    modelBuilder.Entity<StudentCourse>()
        .HasOne(sc => sc.Course)
        .WithMany(c => c.StudentCourses)
        .HasForeignKey(sc => sc.CourseId);
}

A self-referencing association in Entity Framework allows a class or table to
have a relationship with itself. This commonly occurs when dealing with
hierarchal data where each record can have a parent and optionally children of
the same type.


HOW IT SHOULD LOOK

If you visualize the data in a tree structure, think of it as a parent node
(ManagedBy) that potentially has multiple child nodes (Members).

Self-Referencing Association [https://i.stack.imgur.com/eIdpB.png]

In the diagram above, consider a Department class or table. Each department can
be managed by another department, forming a parent-child relationship.


CODE EXAMPLE: DEPARTMENT

Here is the C# code:

public class Department
{
    public int DepartmentId { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }

    // Self-referencing relationship
    public int? ManagedByDepartmentId { get; set; }
    public virtual Department ManagedBy { get; set; }

    public virtual ICollection<Department> DepartmentsManaged { get; set; }
}


In the ManagedBy and DepartmentsManaged properties, let's redirect EF to treat
these properties as our self-referencing relationship using the Fluent API.


FLUENT API CONFIGURATION

Here's how you would use the Fluent API in your DbContext to define the
relationship:

public class YourDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Department> Departments { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        // Configure the self-referencing relationship
        modelBuilder.Entity<Department>()
            .HasOptional(d => d.ManagedBy)
            .WithMany(d => d.DepartmentsManaged)
            .HasForeignKey(d => d.ManagedByDepartmentId);
    }
}


This configuration tells EF that:

 * The ManagedBy property is an optional (nullable) related Department.
 * The back reference is defined through the DepartmentsManaged property.
 * The foreign key for the ManagedByDepartmentId is the key that points back to
   the Department itself.

Let me write the System.Configuration schema and data changes support for Entity
Framework from an MS SQL Server.


VISUAL STUDIO INTEGRATION

Visual Studio provides Code First Migrations for straightforward management of
the database schema and data.

Migrations are accessible via the Package Manager Console. As an example,
executing Update-Database v1 will apply all migrations up to migration v1.


MANUAL CONFIGURATION

As an alternative to the Package Manager Console, you can control EF migrations
through your application's code.

Here is a PowerShell script that restores to a specific version:

# Define your configuration and connection string
$configuration = "YourNamespace.Configuration.v1"
$connectionString = "Data Source=YourDatabase"

# Specify the TargetMigration for the migration
Update-Database -ConfigurationTypeName $configuration -ConnectionString $connectionString -TargetMigration "MigrationName"


For this specific use case of restoring to an older schema, aptly adjust your
configuration by either creating or editing System.Configuration and specifying
the TargetMigration.


API FOR MANAGING MIGRATIONS

The DbMigrator class furnishes a high degree of administrative control over
migrations.

Here is the C# code using the DbMigrator class which is part of the
System.Data.Entity.Migrations namespace for this purpose:

using System.Data.Entity;
using System.Data.Entity.Migrations;

var configuration = new Configuration();
var migrator = new DbMigrator(configuration);

// You need to specify a TargetMigration for the migration
migrator.Update("MigrationName");


Verify the migration's status after running the code. If everything is in order,
the returned result will be true. Conversely, if a problem is encountered, an
error will be prompted.

The following example demonstrates the necessary code:

var pendingMigrations = migrator.GetPendingMigrations();
if (pendingMigrations.Any())
{
    Console.WriteLine("There are pending migrations. Ensure you have the correct TargetMigration.");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Database has been downgraded to the specified migration.");
}

Let's look at the steps to seed a database in Entity Framework Core.


HOW TO SEED A DATABASE

 1. Inherit from DbContext: Extend the DbContext class for your database
    context. Override the OnModelCreating and Seed methods.

 2. Add Migration: Execute the Add-Migration command via Package Manager Console
    to create the migration.

 3. Invoke Seed Method: In Program.cs or Startup.cs, call the Seed method. For
    instance, with the CreateHostBuilder() method in Program.cs.


CODE EXAMPLE: SEED METHOD

Here is the C# code snippet:

public class MyDbContext : DbContext
{
    public MyDbContext(DbContextOptions<MyDbContext> options) 
        : base(options)
    {
    }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        Seed(modelBuilder);
    }

    public virtual void Seed(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        // Seed your database here
    }
}



ADDITIONAL NOTES

 * Default Data: The seed mechanism is suitable for default and test data in
   development.
 * Migrations: This is not appropriate for production databases with existing
   data. Such scenarios require custom migrations.
 * Multiple Data Sets: Each sequential call to Add-Migration creates a migration
   with new or updated data. This can lead to the accumulation of seed data over
   time.


ADVANCED MANAGEMENT

REPLACEDATA

For more advanced management, replace existing data prior to reseeding:

public virtual void Seed(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    modelBuilder.Entity<MyEntity>().HasData(new MyEntity { Id = 1, Name = "Replaced Data" });
}


DISABLE MIGRATIONS

For disabling migrations, create a custom migration script using the SQL DISABLE
TRIGGER statement. Use this carefully, as it can have significant database
impact.

The N+1 problem is a common data persistence issue where EF makes multiple
queries to retrieve related entities rather than leveraging a single query.

To mitigate this problem, use techniques like eager loading, explicit loading,
and projections.


MULTIPLE QUERIES CAUSING THE N+1 PROBLEM

Consider an example of Customer and their related Orders:

var customers = context.Customers.ToList();  

foreach (var customer in customers)  
{  
    var orders = customer.Orders.ToList();  
    // N queries issued for N customers, causing the issue.
}



TECHNIQUES TO AVOID THE N+1 PROBLEM

EAGER LOADING (INCLUDE)

Eager loading allows you to bring in related entities at the time of the primary
entity's query.

var customers = context.Customers.Include(c => c.Orders).ToList();


EXPLICIT LOADING (LOAD)

Explicit loading defers related entities' retrieval until explicitly requested.
It's ideal for scenarios where related data retrieval may vary based on
conditions.

var customer = context.Customers.First();
context.Entry(customer).Collection(c => c.Orders).Load();


PROJECTIONS (SELECT)

Projections allow you to specify only the required fields, avoiding data for
related entities not currently needed.

var customers = context.Customers
    .Select(c => new { Customer = c, Orders = c.Orders.Where(o => o.IsShipped) })
    .ToList();

Proper connection management is pivotal for better Entity Framework performance.
While EF Core often handles this automatically, specific commands optimize the
connection lifecycle.


MANAGING THE CONNECTION LIFECYCLE

 1. Automatic Mode:

    * Default Setting: EF Core operates in an auto-connection mode, opening and
      closing connections as needed.
    * Caveat: Automatic control prevents custom configuration, affecting
      performance in extreme scenarios.

 2. Custom Mode:

    * Developers explicitly open and close connections for improved control,
      especially in scenarios like bulk updates or complex transactions.
    * Caveats: Manual management can introduce human errors and create
      maintenance challenges. It's best suited for advanced applications and
      expert developers.

By comprehending connection modes and practicing appropriate strategies,
developers ensure a balanced approach between automatic and manual control in
connection management.


CODE EXAMPLE: AUTOMATIC MODE

Here is the C# code:

using (var context = new DbContext())
{
    // EF Core manages the connection automatically.
    // Context operations open, use, and close the connection as necessary.
}



CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM MODE

Here is the C# code:

using (var context = new DbContext())
{
    // Provide the context with an open connection.
    context.Database.OpenConnection();

    // Perform required operations using the context.

    // Manually close the connection.
    context.Database.CloseConnection();
}

Entity Framework (EF) offers a mechanism for handling concurrency, allowing
developers to manage data integrity when multiple users interact with the same
data store.


CONCURRENCY CONTROL MECHANISMS

Entity Framework supports several strategies for concurrency management:

 * Optimistic Concurrency: The most common and default mechanism in EF. It
   ensures that no records are inadvertently overwritten by another user without
   their intended changes being considered.

 * Pessimistic Concurrency: EF supports optimistic concurrency. While
   pessimistic concurrency can be implemented using database transactions and
   locks, EF doesn't provide explicit in-built support for this.


TYPES OF CONCURRENCY CONFLICTS

 * Timestamp-based Checks (also known as "Row Versioning"): Detects conflicts
   based on the last update time or version of a record. This technique
   typically uses a timestamp column, which automatically updates when the row
   is modified.

 * Field-level Checks: Compares specific fields to determine if a conflict
   exists.


TIMESTAMP CONCURRENCY IN EF

CONFIGURING TIMESTAMP CONCURRENCY

In EF, you can configure timestamp-based concurrency in your data models using
the [Timestamp] attribute in C#. This marks the property as a concurrency token.

Here's how it's done in code:

public class MyEntity
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    [Timestamp]
    public byte[] RowVersion { get; set; }
}


The RowVersion property is the timestamp concurrency token. It has a special
.HasColumnName() method to specify the actual column name in the database, if
necessary.

OPTIMISTIC CONCURRENCY CHECKS

Optimistic concurrency checks occur automatically in EF when you attempt to save
changes to an object that has a timestamp property.

Here's a typical usage example:

// Retrieve an entity from the context
var entity = dbContext.MyEntities.Find(1);

// Make some changes to the entity
entity.Name = "New Name";

try {
    // Attempt to save changes
    dbContext.SaveChanges();
} catch (DbUpdateConcurrencyException) {
    // Handle the exception
}


If another user has updated the same record since you originally queried it, a
DbUpdateConcurrencyException is thrown, indicating a concurrency conflict. It's
then up to the developer to decide how to handle this exception, potentially by
reloading the entity and reapplying the changes.

Entity Framework supports a clear, consistent approach to using inheritance,
employing a hierarchy of classes linked to the database through different
strategies. The primary strategies include:

 * Table Per Hierarchy (TPH): Merges all hierarchy types into a single database
   table.
 * Table Per Type (TPT): Each class in the hierarchy corresponds to a different
   database table.
 * Table Per Concrete Type (TPC): Each class in the hierarchy is mapped to an
   individual table.


CODE EXAMPLE: TPH INHERITANCE

Here is the C# code:

public abstract class Person
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

public class Student : Person
{
    public string StudentId { get; set; }
}

public class Teacher : Person
{
    public string TeacherId { get; set; }
}



TPH INHERITANCE MAPPING IN ENTITY FRAMEWORK

EF Core leverages Fluent API via the OnModelCreating method in DbContext to
define inheritance mapping. The example below uses TPH:

protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    modelBuilder.Entity<Person>()
        .HasDiscriminator<string>("Discriminator")
        .HasValue<Student>("Student")
        .HasValue<Teacher>("Teacher");

    // Additional configurations if needed.
}


When you execute a model migration, you will observe a single table representing
the hierarchy model. The schema should have a Discriminator column, enabling EF
to distinguish between different types within the hierarchy.


CODE EXAMPLE: TPT INHERITANCE

Here is the C# code:

[Table("Persons")]
public abstract class Person
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

[Table("Students")]
public class Student : Person
{
    public string StudentId { get; set; }
}

[Table("Teachers")]
public class Teacher : Person
{
    public string TeacherId { get; set; }
}



TPT INHERITANCE MAPPING IN ENTITY FRAMEWORK

The mapping is driven through attributes in this example. When EF Core inspects
the classes and finds the Table attribute, it interprets the model as
implementing TPT inheritance.


CODE EXAMPLE: TPC INHERITANCE

Here is the C# code:

[Table("Persons")]
public class Person
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

[Table("Students")]
public class Student : Person
{
    public string StudentId { get; set; }
}

[Table("Teachers")]
public class Teacher : Person
{
    public string TeacherId { get; set; }
}



TPC INHERITANCE MAPPING IN ENTITY FRAMEWORK

This inheritance strategy uses both table attributes and class hierarchies. Each
derived class represents a distinct table in the database, as indicated by the
Table attribute on the derived classes.

Entity Framework (EF) is designed to work primarily with database models.
However, you can also devise ways for EF to interact with view-models.

Manipulating view-models directly with EF is possible, but it comes with
potential pitfalls

One such pitfall is that the changes made to these view-models are not tracked
by entity framework and won't be persisted to the database when SaveChanges() is
called.

It's generally recommended to keep the responsibilities of your view-model and
database models separate to better conform with separation of concerns
principles. View-models are used for presentation and user interactivity, while
database models handle data and database interactions.

When necessary, it's common to craft separate layers of abstraction, such as a
Service Layer, that can interface with both your view-models and your EF-managed
database models.


CODE EXAMPLE: USING A SERVICE LAYER

Here is the C# code:

public interface IMyService
{
    void UpdateVM(MyViewModel vm);
}

public class MyService : IMyService
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;

    public MyService(DbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    public void UpdateVM(MyViewModel vm)
    {
        var dbModel = _context.Set<MyEntity>().Find(vm.Id);
        // Map changes from vm to dbModel
        _context.SaveChanges();
    }
}

Entity Framework enables operations across multiple database entries through
DbContext instances.

However, it's essential to note that each DbContext represents its Unit of Work
(UoW), meaning you must take measures for transactions spanning across different
contexts.


TRANSACTIONS WITH MULTIPLE DBCONTEXT INSTANCES

While it's preferable to use a single DbContext for a transaction, here's how to
handle multi-context transactions, especially in more complex scenarios.

STEP 1: BEGIN A TRANSACTION FOR EACH CONTEXT

Start a transaction for each involved DbContext. This way, operations within
each context are either cumulatively committed or rolled back.

CODE EXAMPLE: BEGIN TRANSACTIONS

Here is the C# code:

using (var context1 = new MyContext())
using (var context2 = new MyContext())
using (var transaction1 = context1.Database.BeginTransaction())
using (var transaction2 = context2.Database.BeginTransaction())
{
    try
    {
        // Perform some context specific operations
        context1.SaveChanges();
        context2.SaveChanges();

        // Commit both the transactions
        transaction1.Commit();
        transaction2.Commit();
    }
    catch
    {
        // If there is an exception, roll back both transactions
        transaction1.Rollback();
        transaction2.Rollback();
    }
}


STEP 2: NEST THE SAVECHANGES CALLS WITHIN THE TRANSACTION SCOPE

To ensure that related context updates occur atomically, nest the SaveChanges
calls within the transaction scope.

Keep in mind that in certain scenarios, all changes might not be immediately
visible within the same transaction if both reads and writes occur.

STEP 3: COMMIT OR ROLL BACK ALL TRANSACTIONS

On successful completion, commit all involved transactions. Conversely, if any
step within any DbContext fails, roll back the transactions to maintain data
integrity.


OPTIMIZING FOR A SINGLE CONTEXT

In many scenarios, efficiency and data consistency are best managed using a
single DbContext within a transaction. If possible, streamline your coding
practices to avoid the complexities of multi-context transactions.

Yes, you can unit test code built with Entity Framework. A common practice
involves using an in-memory database for streamlined testing.


TECHNIQUES FOR TESTING EF-BASED APPLICATIONS

 1. Repository and Unit of Work Pattern: Implement a separate set of
    repositories and unit of work layers that interact with EF. You can then
    test these components in isolation.

 2. In-Memory Database: Both EF Core and EF 6 support in-memory databases, ideal
    for fast, isolated unit tests.

 3. Microsoft Fakes (Legacy): For older versions of EF, using Microsoft Fakes
    from Visual Studio enables you to mock or stub DbContext and DbSet objects
    for more controlled testing.

 4. PAckage Moq is a popular choice for creating mock objects in .NET. You can
    use it along with Moq to configure and verify the behavior of your DbContext
    methods.

Here is the C# code:

// SETUP
var data = new List<Product> {
    new Product { Id = 1, Name = "Product 1" },
    new Product { Id = 2, Name = "Product 2" },
}.AsQueryable();

var mockSet = new Mock<DbSet<Product>>();
mockSet.As<IQueryable<Product>>().Setup(m => m.Provider).Returns(data.Provider);
mockSet.As<IQueryable<Product>>().Setup(m => m.Expression).Returns(data.Expression);
mockSet.As<IQueryable<Product>>().Setup(m => m.ElementType).Returns(data.ElementType);
mockSet.As<IQueryable<Product>>().Setup(m => m.GetEnumerator()).Returns(data.GetEnumerator());

var mockContext = new Mock<MyDbContext>();
mockContext.Setup(c => c.Products).Returns(mockSet.Object);

// EXERCISE & VERIFY
var service = new ProductService(mockContext.Object);
service.DeleteProduct(1);
mockSet.Verify(m => m.Remove(It.IsAny<Product>()), Times.Once());

// TEARDOWN


For EF Core, code might look like this:

// SETUP
var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<MyDbContext>()
    .UseInMemoryDatabase("TestProductDb")
    .Options;

using (var context = new MyDbContext(options))
{
    context.Products.Add(new Product { Id = 1, Name = "Product 1" });
    context.Products.Add(new Product { Id = 2, Name = "Product 2" });
    context.SaveChanges();
}

// EXERCISE & VERIFY
using (var context = new MyDbContext(options))
{
    var service = new ProductService(context);
    service.DeleteProduct(1);

    Assert.Equal(1, context.Products.Count());
}

// TEARDOWN
using (var context = new MyDbContext(options))
{
    context.Database.EnsureDeleted();
}

Dependency Injection (DI) delegates the responsibility for creating and managing
object dependencies to an external framework, like .NET Core. Such a design
approach enhances modularity, testability and maintainability.


KEY COMPONENTS

 * Client: The component that requires a service.
 * Service: The injected dependency.
 * Container: The interface that establishes the binding between the service and
   the client.


HOW DI WORKS

 1. Registration: In the Composition Root, the container is configured to
    associate abstractions with their concrete implementations.
 2. Resolution: The container is responsible for providing the appropriate
    concrete implementation to the client.


COMMON DI PATTERNS

 * Constructor Injection: Dependencies are provided through the constructor of
   the dependent class.
 * Property Injection: Dependencies are set using public properties or methods.


CODE EXAMPLE: CONSTRUCTOR INJECTION

Here is the C# code:

public class UserRepository : IUserRepository
{
    private readonly AppDbContext _context;

    // Constructor Injection
    public UserRepository(AppDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }
}


In the Startup.cs:

public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    // Register the AppDbContext and the repository
    services.AddDbContext<AppDbContext>(options => options.UseSqlServer(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection")));
    services.AddScoped<IUserRepository, UserRepository>();
}

When faced with Entity Framework performance challenges, here are several
diagnostic and optimization strategies to explore:


DIAGNOSTIC STEPS

 1. Efficiency Metrics Assessment: Consider both database and application-side
    metrics relevant to EF performance:

    * Database Metrics: Identify slow queries and monitor server resource usage.
    * Application Metrics: Evaluate factors such as the amount of data being
      loaded and the number of database round-trips. Tools like EF Profiler can
      be especially useful here.

 2. Identify Bottlenecks using Profilers: Choose a profiler that works well with
    EF. Use it to see which queries take the most time, how often they are
    executed, and what underlying SQL is generated.

 3. Code Inspection: Perform a thorough examination of the codebase to pinpoint
    any potential performance pitfalls, such as unneeded eager loading or
    extensive object graphs.

 4. Query and Execution Plan Analysis:

    * SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS): Use Query Execution Plan to check for
      query bottlenecks and ways to optimize.
    * SQL Profiler: Trace and analyze how SQL statements are functioning in
      real-time.
    * SQL Query Tuning: This approach is effective for complex queries that
      demonstrate poor performance, especially after analyzing the query
      execution plan.

 5. Database Tuning: Normalize database data and validate hardware and tuning
    configuration for the database server.


TUNING AND OPTIMIZATION

IN-MEMORY CACHE IMPLEMENTATION

One effective way to optimize EF performance is by introducing an in-memory
cache mechanism to reduce recurrent database calls, best for read-heavy
applications over large datasets. Redis, Memcached, or a distributed cache are
common choices.

Below is the C#:

public class MyDbContext : DbContext
{
    public MyDbContext()
    {
        // Disable automatic change tracking for improved performance in read-heavy scenarios
        ChangeTracker.QueryTrackingBehavior = QueryTrackingBehavior.NoTracking;
    }

    public List<Customer> GetCustomers()
    {
        var cacheKey = "Customers";  // Consider using better cache keys
        if (!MemoryCache.Default.Contains(cacheKey))
        {
            var customers = Customers.ToList();
            MemoryCache.Default.Add(cacheKey, customers, DateTimeOffset.MaxValue);
        }
        return MemoryCache.Default.Get(cacheKey) as List<Customer>;
    }
}


ASYNCHRONOUS QUERY EXECUTION

Leverage asynchronous methods in EF. This is especially beneficial in scenarios
where database operations can run concurrently with application tasks.

Here is the C# code:

public async Task<List<Customer>> GetCustomersAsync()
{
    using (var context = new MyDbContext())
    {
        return await context.Customers.ToListAsync();
    }
}


LAZY LOADING AND EAGER LOADING STRATEGIES

Optimize entity loading with these strategies:

 * Use Lazy Loading when dealing with large datasets and need to load entities
   on-demand.
 * Eager loading, on the other hand, is preferable when multiple entities are to
   be retrieved in one go. The .Include() method is often used for this.

Here is an example:

// Lazy Loading: Loads orders only when accessed
public virtual ICollection<Order> Orders { get; set; }

// Eager Loading: Loads orders at the time of customer fetching
var customers = context.Customers.Include(c => c.Orders).ToList();


DATA ACCESS LAYER REFINEMENT

Keep the data access code consolidated in a dedicated layer and assess
efficiency across its components. Furthermore, utilize stored procedures in EF
to bring about further performance gains.

Here is the C# code:

public class CustomerRepository
{
    private MyDbContext _context;

    public CustomerRepository(MyDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    public List<Customer> GetCustomersUsingStoredProcedure()
    {
        return _context.Database.SqlQuery<Customer>("exec GetCustomers").ToList();
    }
}


BATCHING STATEMENTS FOR MULTIPLE OPERATIONS

Minimize round-trips to the database server by grouping similar operations. This
can lead to enhanced performance, particularly when dealing with a substantial
number of entities.

Here is the C#:

public void SaveBatchOfCustomers(List<Customer> customers)
{
    using (var context = new MyDbContext())
    {
        context.Customers.AddRange(customers);
        context.SaveChanges();
    }
}


CONTEXT LIFETIME OPTIMIZATION

Assess and restrict the lifecycle of your DbContext. As a rule of thumb, keep
the scope as narrow as reasonable.

Here is the C#:

// Using a context per operation, potentially split across entities, then disposed.
public void PerformMultipleContextOperations()
{
    using (var context1 = new MyDbContext())
    using (var context2 = new MyDbContext())
    {
        var customer = new Customer { Name = "John" };
        context1.Customers.Add(customer);
        context1.SaveChanges();

        // Do some processing...

        customer.Age = 35;
        context2.Entry(customer).State = EntityState.Modified;
        context2.SaveChanges();
    }
}



CONTINUOUS VIGILANCE

The process of performance optimization in EF doesn't conclude with its
execution. Continuous monitoring of your application's performance in production
and fine-tuning whenever necessary are pivotal to guaranteeing a consistent and
high-performing user experience.

Choose indicators and metrics, like average number of queries or average query
time, and monitor them routinely to ascertain that your application is meeting
performance benchmarks.

Moreover, regularly inspect and track SQL server performance metrics to ensure
that it is realms away from performance degradation.

Entity Framework provides several ways to debug generated SQL queries, giving
you the necessary insights during development.


USING TOSTRING

You can access the raw SQL generated by a LINQ query using the ToString method
on the query.

Here is the C# code:


using (var context = new YourDbContext())
{
    var query = context.YourEntity.Where(e => e.SomeProperty == "SomeValue");

    var sql = query.ToString();

    Console.WriteLine(sql);
}



EXTENSIVE LOGGING

Entity Framework Core allows you to configure logging at different levels,
providing detail about database operations.

Here is the C# code:


using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var loggerFactory = LoggerFactory.Create(builder =>
{
    builder
        .AddFilter((category, level) =>
            category == DbLoggerCategory.Database.Command.Name && level == LogLevel.Information)
        .AddConsole();
});

using (var context = new YourDbContext(new DbContextOptionsBuilder<YourDbContext>()
    .UseLoggerFactory(loggerFactory)
    .Options))
{
