    var result = query.ToList();
}



INTERACTING WITH EVENTS

You can leverage the Diagnostics event available in the latest versions of
Entity Framework Core to capture and act on database queries.

Here is the C# code:


using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

using (var context = new YourDbContext())
{
    var query = context.YourEntity.Where(e => e.SomeProperty == "SomeValue");

    var result = query.ToList();
}

context.Database.GetDiagnostics()
    .QueryCompleted
    .Subscribe(args => Console.WriteLine(args.ToQueryString()));

Here are potential reasons for entity states not updating as expected, along
with corresponding solutions:


COMMON ROOT CAUSES

 1. Entity Context Mismatch: Using different instances of DbContext in the UI
    and business layers can cause inconsistencies. Ensure a single DbContext
    instance is used or handle state transitions accordingly.
 2. Optimistic Concurrency Control: In a multi-user environment, concurrent
    changes to the same entity can lead to potential data loss. You might need
    to tailor your approach to concurrency resolution using the Timestamp
    attribute or RowVersion property.


ADVANCED TROUBLESHOOTING

 * Turning off Tracking: While useful for certain scenarios like read-only
   operations, "No Tracking" in EF Core can inadvertently disable entity state
   tracking. Ensure entities are appropriately either tracked or not.

 * Relational Dependency Issues: Incorrect foreign key relationships, navigation
   properties, or entity associations can lead to cascading update or delete
   problems.

 * Programmatic Pitfalls: In Windows Services, Hangfire, or other long-running
   processes, using a single DbContext instance throughout its lifecycle can
   lead to Entity Metadata or query pipeline issues.


SOLUTIONS

PERMISSIONS AND CONSTRAINTS FOR DATABASES

 * Controlled update or delete permissions: When update or deletion operations
   fail, it might be due to constraints in place. Ensure proper permissions and
   constraints on related tables.

CODE SAMPLE: HANDLING CONCURRENCY

Here is the C# code:

public ActionResult Edit(int id)
{
    var existingProduct = db.Products.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Id == id);
    if (existingProduct == null)
    {
        return NotFound();
    }

    // Submit changes assuming concurrency
    try
    {
        db.Entry(existingProduct).OriginalValues["RowVersion"] = rowVersionFromUser;
        db.SaveChanges();
        return RedirectToAction("Index");
    }
    catch (DbUpdateConcurrencyException ex)
    {
        var entry = ex.Entries.Single();
        var clientValues = entry.CurrentValues;
        var databaseEntry = entry.GetDatabaseValues();
        if (databaseEntry == null)
        {
            ModelState.AddModelError(string.Empty, "Unable to save changes. The product was deleted by another user.");
        }
        else
        {
            var databaseValues = databaseEntry.ToObject();
            // Refresh client and database values for display
            ModelState.AddModelError(string.Empty, "The record you attempted to edit was modified by another user after you got the original value.");
            existingProduct.RowVersion = (byte[])databaseValues.GetType().GetProperty("RowVersion").GetValue(databaseValues, null);
            ModelState.SetModelValue("RowVersion", new ValueProviderResult(databaseValues.GetType().GetProperty("RowVersion").GetValue(databaseValues, null).ToString(), 
                databaseValues.GetType().GetProperty("RowVersion").GetValue(databaseValues, null).ToString(), System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture));
        }
        return View(existingProduct);
    }
}

Let's look at the three primary methodologies for managing the lifecycle of an
Entity Framework DbContext: Transient, Scoped, and Singleton. Each of these
aligns better with certain application types and use-cases.


TRANSIENT

A new DbContext is created each time it is required. With this method, you can
incorporate dependency injection in your application to ensure objects are
decoupled and have a short lifespan.

EXAMPLE: DEPENDENCY INJECTION WITH TRANSIENT DBCONTEXT

Here is the C# code:

// Configure the DBContext as transient for DI container
services.AddDbContext<YourDbContext>(ServiceLifetime.Transient);

// Request a DB context
public class YourService
{
    private readonly YourDbContext _context;

    public YourService(YourDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    // Method using the context
    // ...
}



SCOPED

The DbContext is created per request or client use. In multi-user applications,
each user or request gets its own DbContext. The DbContext is disposed of when
the scope is complete, achieving resource cleanup.

EXAMPLE: HTTP REQUEST SCOPED DBCONTEXT

Here is the C# code:

// Register the DB context with HTTP request scope
services.AddDbContext<YourDbContext>(ServiceLifetime.Scoped);

// In an API Controller
public class YourController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly YourDbContext _context;

    public YourController(YourDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    // ... API actions using the context
}



SINGLETON

The DbContext is instantiated once and shared across the application lifespan.
This might lead to thread safety concerns in multi-threaded environments. Its
use should be limited to thread-safe scenarios or read-only operations.

EXAMPLE: SINGLETON DBCONTEXT

Here is the C# code:

// Register the DB context as a singleton
services.AddDbContext<YourDbContext>(ServiceLifetime.Singleton);

// In a controller
public class YourController : ControllerBase
{
    static YourDbContext _context;

    static YourController()
    {
        var sp = new ServiceCollection().AddDbContext<YourDbContext>(ServiceLifetime.Singleton).BuildServiceProvider();
        _context = sp.GetRequiredService<YourDbContext>();
    }

    // ... Other actions using the static context
}



HYBRID APPROACHES AND ADDITIONAL CONSIDERATIONS

Some applications may employ hybrid methods such as transient DbContexts for
read operations and scoped ones for more significant, e.g., write, operations.
However, this can result in increased complexity and should be done with
caution.

Additionally, there are some cases when using a lifetime that is too long, like
Singleton (especially in web applications), can lead to negative consequences
such as a stagnant data context.

Selecting the appropriate method for your DbContext is vital to ensure its
resources are managed effectively. Scoped tends to be the most common choice for
web applications due to its match with the HTTP request-response cycle.

In Entity Framework, connection string security is crucial, especially when
dealing with sensitive data. Common best practices involve using environment
variables for development and configurations via vault services for production.


BEST PRACTICES

 * Environment Variables: A simple yet effective technique for local
   development.
 * Azure Key Vault: Integration with Azure for a security-focused build and
   deployment pipeline.
 * Secrets Manager: Amazon's approach to securely storing sensitive data.


CODE WITH BEST PRACTICES

USING ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES ON LOCAL ENVIRONMENT

C# provides two ways to access environment variables: System.Environment and
System.Configuration.ConfigurationManager.

Here we use System.Configuration.ConfigurationManager.ConnectionStrings to
access the connection string set in the local environment:

using System.Configuration;

var connectionString = ConfigurationManager.ConnectionStrings["YourConnectionStringAlias"].ConnectionString;


For this approach to work, you need to set the environment variable
'YourConnectionStringAlias' in your development environment, such as Visual
Studio.

AZURE KEY VAULT INTEGRATION

Azure Key Vault is a cloud service for managing cryptographic keys and other
secrets.

To fetch the connection string from Azure Key Vault, you would typically
retrieve a secret using a client library such as
Azure.Security.KeyVault.Secrets:

using Azure.Core;
using Azure.Identity;
using Azure.Security.KeyVault.Secrets;

// Create a token credential
TokenCredential tokenCredential = new DefaultAzureCredential();

// Create a new secret client using the vault endpoint and the client credentials
var client = new SecretClient(new Uri("https://your-key-vault.vault.azure.net/"), tokenCredential);

// Retrieve the secret using its name
KeyVaultSecret secret = client.GetSecret("YourSecretName");


In this code, your-key-vault.vault.azure.net is the Endpoint of your Azure Key
Vault and YourSecretName is the name of the secret containing the connection
string.

AWS SECRETS MANAGER

For AWS, the process is similar. Let's look at how you would retrieve a secret
from AWS Secrets Manager:

using Amazon;
using Amazon.SecretsManager;
using Amazon.SecretsManager.Model;

// Create a Secrets Manager client
var client = new AmazonSecretsManagerClient(RegionEndpoint.USWest2);

// Retrieve the secret using its ARN
GetSecretValueResponse response = client.GetSecretValue(new GetSecretValueRequest
{
    SecretId = "YourSecretARN"
});


In this code, YourSecretARN is the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the secret
containing the connection string.

When using Entity Framework in a multi-user environment, it's essential to
consider several security aspects to ensure data integrity and prevent
unauthorized access.


CONCURRENCY

VISUAL STUDIO CONFIGURATION

 1. Enable: In edmx file, set "Concurrenc Mode" to "Fixed" for the relevant
    property.

 2. Disable: As-is setup where "Concurrency Mode" is undefined. Will retain the
    last write, leading to potential data loss. This is the default setting in
    EF.

 3. Exception Handling: Subscription to "SaveChanges" to capture conflict events
    via OptimisticConcurrencyException.


CODE EXAMPLE: CONCURRENCY CHECKS WITH EF6

Here is the C# code:

// Add Tables
public class YourContext : DbContext {
    public YourContext() : base("name=YourContext") { }
    public DbSet<YourTable> YourTables { get; set; }

    // Method to ensure Concurrency checks
    protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder) {
        modelBuilder.Entity<YourTable>().Property(p => p.RowVersion).IsConcurrencyToken();
    }
}

// Update Data
var existingRecord = context.YourTables.Find(id);
existingRecord.Property1 = "NewValue";
context.Entry(existingRecord).OriginalValues["RowVersion"] = rowVersionAsByteArray;
context.SaveChanges();



STRICT TYPE CHECKS

 * Recommendation: Apply stringent type checks to validate data before any
   database operations.
 * Impact: Helps mitigate possible SQL injection risks.

HOW TO CONFIGURE IN VISUAL STUDIO

 1. Prevent: Enable "Validate On Save" mode in the Entity Data Model.
 2. Handling of Invalid Data: This setting ensures Entity Framework detects
    discrepancies, and an exception is raised if the data type doesn't match
    with the one in the database.


THE CONSUMER OF EF

 1. Role: Entity Framework works as a liaison between the application and the
    database.

 2. Implications: Understanding its role helps developers appreciate possible
    security gaps and identify areas to manage persistence operations and data
    validation manually.


ROLE-BASED SECURITY

 * Recommendation: Configure role-based security to oversee user actions
   regarding persistence.


CODE EXAMPLE: ROLE-BASED ACCESS CONTROL

Here is the C# code:

public class YourContext : DbContext {
    public YourContext() : base("name=YourContext") { }
    public DbSet<YourTable> YourTables { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder) {
        modelBuilder.Entity<YourTable>().HasKey(u => u.Id).HasMany(u => u.Roles).WithMany(r => r.Users);
    }
}

public class YourTable {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public ICollection<Role> Roles { get; set; }
}

public class Role {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public ICollection<YourTable> Users { get; set; }
}

// Role-Based Validation
var user = context.YourTables.Include("Roles").FirstOrDefault(u => u.Id == userId);
if (user != null && user.Roles.Any(r => r.Name.Equals("Admin"))) {
    // Only authorized Admin users can update the record
    user.Property1 = "NewValue";
    context.SaveChanges();
}


In this example, "User" and "Role" classes establish a many-to-many
relationship, ensuring that only users with the "Admin" role can update a
specific record.


SECRETS AND CONFIGURATION

 1. Protection Mechanism: Safeguard sensitive data, such as connection strings,
    using tools like Azure Key Vault or placeholders in configuration files that
    aren't committed to version control.

 2. Context-Aware Usage: Configure these measures at the application level.


TRANSACTIONS

 1. Indispensability: Employ database transactions to guarantee atomicity,
    consistency, isolation, and durability (ACID).

 2. Authentication: Integrate with user authentication, ensuring the user has
    the necessary privileges before starting a database transaction.


CODE EXAMPLE: TRANSACTION HANDLING

Here is the C# code:

public void UpdateMultipleRecords() {
    using (var context = new YourContext()) {
        using (var dbContextTransaction = context.Database.BeginTransaction()) {
            try {
                // Make changes to multiple records
                // ...

                context.SaveChanges();

                dbContextTransaction.Commit();
            } catch (Exception) {
                dbContextTransaction.Rollback();
                throw;
            }
        }
    }
}


 3. Exception Handling: Employ comprehensive error handling to manage any errors
    that might crop up during a transaction, rolling back changes if necessary.

Azure Cosmos DB supports Entity Framework through a dedicated provider tailored
to this multi-modal database.


USING COSMOS DB WITH EF

 1. Setup: When adding an Azure Cosmos DB data connection in your solution,
    ensure that you have the Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Cosmos package
    installed.

 2. Configuration: In your DbContext class, specify that you are using Cosmos as
    a provider with the UseCosmos() function.

 3. Define Entities: Design entities that you intend to persist in Cosmos DB,
    bearing in mind its unique attributes, such as multimodal storage and
    support for distributed architectures.

 4. Understanding Limitations: Although EF Core provides a high level of query
    abstraction, it's essential to comprehend the unique capabilities and
    constraints of Cosmos DB. For instance, Cosmos DB doesn't support all SQL
    functions.

 5. General Tips: Be aware of partition/telemetry keys and throughput.
    Additionally, minimize the number of Remote API Calls for better
    performance, and leverage Change Feed for near-real-time capabilities.


USING DBCONTEXT IN COSMOS DB

Here is the C# code:

using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

// Define the entity
public class Customer
{
    [Key]
    public string Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

// The DbContext to interact with the database
public class MyCosmosDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Customer> Customers { get; set; }

    protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
    {
        optionsBuilder.UseCosmos(
            "YourConnectionString",
            "YourDatabase",
            "YourContainer"
        );
    }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        using (var context = new MyCosmosDbContext())
        {
            var newCustomer = new Customer
            {
                Id = Guid.NewGuid().ToString(),
                Name = "John Doe"
            };

            context.Customers.Add(newCustomer);

            context.SaveChanges();
        }
    }
}

Azure, with its range of PaaS and SaaS offerings, provides a versatile platform
for building microservice architectures powered by Entity Framework.


