In a cross-platform database environment, certain database-specific functions
may not be available on all systems. This can pose a challenge in executing such
functions in a database-agnostic way using Entity Framework (EF).


ADDRESSING FUNCTION INCOMPATIBILITY

LEVERAGING QUERYABLE EXTENSIONS

Using a direct SQL approach with EF lets you execute database-specific
functions.

using System.Linq;

var result = context.Entities
    .Where(e => EF.Functions.Like(e.Property, "pattern"))
    .ToList();


Although this approach proves efficient, it is platform-specific, potentially
leading to inconsistencies when operating across different databases.

EMPLOYING .SELECT() FOR CROSS-PLATFORM VALIDATIONS

Integration of .Select() enables you to apply cross-database validation after
executing the platform-specific function, enhancing consistency.

var result = context.Entities
    .Where(e => EF.Functions.Like(e.Property, "pattern"))
    .Select(e => new { Entity = e, IsMatch = EF.Functions.Like(e.Property, "pattern")})
    .AsEnumerable()
    .Where(e => e.IsMatch)
    .Select(e => e.Entity)
    .ToList();


Though beneficial, this method is less efficient compared to direct SQL
execution and may require extra caution with large datasets due to its in-memory
processing.

CENTRALIZING DATABASE LOGIC WITH USER-DEFINED FUNCTIONS

Creation and use of user-defined functions (UDF) in your model can help
streamline database-specific operations.

dbContext.Database.ExecuteSqlRaw("CREATE FUNCTION ...");


While UDFs are database-specific, they provide both the efficiency of direct SQL
execution and the consistency of an EF query.


UNIFIED CODE EXAMPLE

Here is the C# code:

using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using System;
using System.Linq;

public class MyEntity
{
    public int Id {get; set;}
    public string Property { get; set; }
}

public class MyDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<MyEntity> Entities { get; set; }

    protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
    {
        var connection = "connection_string_here";
        optionsBuilder.UseSqlServer(connection);
    }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        modelBuilder.HasDbFunction(() => EF.Functions.Like(default(string), default(string)))
            .HasName("LIKE");
    }
}

