Migrating code from Entity Framework 6 (EF6) to Entity Framework Core (EF Core)
involves several steps to adapt the data access layer for better performance and
flexibility.


KEY CHALLENGES IN MIGRATION

 1. API Changes: EF6 and EF Core have different APIs for database interaction.
 2. Behavioral Changes: Some behavior, such as model configuration, differs
    between the two versions.
 3. Missing Features: EF Core might lack certain features present in EF6.


STEPS FOR MIGRATION

1. UPDATE NUGET PACKAGES AND DEPENDENCIES

 * First, update the EF6 and other related packages to the latest version.

dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore
dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design
# Additional packages if needed:
# dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer
# dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Tools


2. RESOLVE API DIFFERENCES

 * Replace EF6's constructs with their EF Core equivalents. For example, replace
   SaveChanges with SaveChanges or SaveChangesAsync.
 * Consider using the EF Upgrade Assistant tool for help in changing code.The
   tool will identify common upgrade issues, such as obsolete methods.

// Replace this in EF6
var book = context.Books.SingleOrDefault(b => b.Id == id);

// With this in EF Core
var book = context.Books.Find(id);


3. HANDLE THE CHANGE IN CONFIGURATION

 * While OnModelCreating from EF6 is similar to its Core counterpart, ensure you
   update ModelBuilder usages, key mapping, and relations.

 * Fluent API declarations can also be different, e.g., from HasKey to HasKey.
   -EF Core uses the HasConversion method to convert between types, whereas EF6
   uses the IDbModelCacheKey property.

 * EF Core provides a HasDefaultValueSql method that EF6 does not provide.

// EF6
modelBuilder.Entity<Person>().Property(p => p.BirthDate).HasColumnName("Birthday");

// EF Core
modelBuilder.Entity<Person>().Property(p => p.BirthDate).HasColumnName("Birthday");
modelBuilder.Entity<Blog>()
    .Property(p => p.Rating)
    .HasConversion(
        v => (int)v,
        v => (Rating)v
    )
    .HasColumnType("enum('Low', 'High')")
    .HasDefaultValue(Rating.Low);


4. MODIFY QUERIES

 * Transition LINQ queries to EF Core-appropriate syntax.
 * Explicit Loading: EF Core uses the Load method, while EF6 uses Include.
 * Raw SQL Queries: EF Core adopts raw SQL through FromSqlRaw, coupled with the
   ExecuteSqlCommand.
 * The Include Method: It is more flexible in EF Core and requires updating to
   take advantage of the improved functionality.

5. ADJUST THE CODEBASE

 * Review and update code that might be influenced by changes in behavior or
   missing features.

6. TEST THE MODIFICATIONS THOROUGHLY

 * Validate that the modified codebase upholds the migration goals and doesn't
   introduce new issues.
 * Execute both unit tests and integration tests to ascertain that the database
   action is consistent.


CODE EXAMPLE: CONTEXT UPDATE

Here is the C# code:

// EF6
public class LibraryContext : DbContext
{
    public LibraryContext() : base("name=LibraryContext") { }
    public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
    protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        // Model Configuration
        base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);
    }
}

// EF Core
public class LibraryContext : DbContext
{
    public LibraryContext(DbContextOptions<LibraryContext> options) : base(options) { }
    public DbSet<Book> Books { get; set; }
    public DbSet<Author> Authors { get; set; }
    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        // Model Configuration
        base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);
    }
}

Entity Framework (EF) provides several strategies for initializing databases,
which can vary from the simplest approach of creating databases if they don't
exist to more specialized solutions like migrations.


EF DATABASE INITIALIZATION STRATEGIES

 1. Create Database If Not Exists

    This strategy ensures that if there's no database defined for the context,
    one is created. However, if the model changes, this method won't update the
    database to reflect the changes.

    By Data Annotation:

    using System.Data.Entity;

    public class MyContext : DbContext
    {
        public MyContext() : base("name=MyContext")
        {
            Database.SetInitializer(new CreateDatabaseIfNotExists<MyContext>());
        }
    }


    By Fluent API:

    using System.Data.Entity;

    modelBuilder.Entity<Blog>()
        .Map(m => m
            .AutoMap(DERIVED)
            .Table("blogs"))
        .Map<ReadOnlyBlog>(m => m.ToTable("ReadOnlyBlogs"));


 2. DropCreateDatabaseAlways or DropCreateAlways

    These strategies drop the existing database and create a new one each time
    the application is initialized. While these methods are good for quick
    development and testing, they should not be used in production.

    By Data Annotation:

    using System.Data.Entity;

    public class MyContext : DbContext
    {
        public MyContext() : base("name=MyContext")
        {
            Database.SetInitializer(new DropCreateDatabaseAlways<MyContext>());
        }
    }


    Quick Tip:
    To specifically use "DropCreateDatabaseAlways" or "DropCreateAlways", create
    an initializer instance:

    Database.SetInitializer(new DropCreateDatabaseAlways<MyContext>());


 3. MigrateDatabaseToLatestVersion

    This strategy uses migrations to ensure the database is up-to-date with the
    latest model. If the database doesn't exist, it will be created and all
    pending migrations will be applied.

    By Data Annotation:

    using System.Data.Entity;

    public class MyContext : DbContext
    {
        public MyContext() : base("name=MyContext")
        {
            Database.SetInitializer(new MigrateDatabaseToLatestVersion<MyContext, Configuration>());
        }
    }


    Make sure that Configuration is enabling migrations for your context.

 4. Custom Initializers

    Developers can also create their own custom initializers by extending
    IDatabaseInitializer. This approach is flexible and can cater to specific
    requirements that aren't covered by the built-in strategies.

    Order of Initialization:
    Ensure that Database.SetInitializer is called before any operation that
    would touch the database or access the context. The best practice is to set
    the initializer in the constructor of the context.

    Example of Custom Initializer:

    public class MyDropCreateDatabaseIfModelChanges : DropCreateDatabaseIfModelChanges<MyContext>
    {
        protected override void Seed(MyContext context)
        {
            // Add seed data here
        }
    }
    public class MyContext : DbContext
    {
        public MyContext()
        : base("name=MyContext")
        {
            Database.SetInitializer(new MyDropCreateDatabaseIfModelChanges());
        }
    }



BEST PRACTICES

 * Development Environment:

   * For rapid iteration, consider using methods like "DropCreateDatabaseAlways"
     for a consistently clean start.
   * Move to more precise strategies, like "MigrateDatabaseToLatestVersion," as
     your model stabilizes.

 * Production Environment:

   * Aim for stability by relying on the default, create-database-if-not-exists
     strategy.
   * Ensure thorough testing if any migration strategies are implemented.


FURTHER CONSIDERATIONS

 * Execution Time: Initialization strategies are primarily executed during the
   first operation that requires a database to be interacted with in a context.
   This means they can be set at any time before the context is used, but they
   are not executed until the first database operation occurs.
 * Integration with Migrations: Using "MigrateDatabaseToLatestVersion" with EF
   Code First Migrations takes care of both schema and data modifications,
   making it a powerful all-in-one solution.


RECOMMENDATIONS

 * For quick prototyping, consider the "DropCreateDatabaseAlways" method.
 * For consistent development, implement more predictable strategies.
 * In production, use a cautious approach: design the database first, carry out
   extensive testing, and utilize "CreateDatabaseIfNotExists".

While Entity Framework is primarily designed for SQL-based databases, you can
indeed integrate it with non-supported data sources.

This is achieved through custom providers, enabling EF to connect with diverse
systems like NoSQL databases.


CUSTOM EF PROVIDERS

To work with non-NET databases using EF, you typically create a library that
adheres to the EF Core Provider model and implements the necessary interfaces.
Below are the implementations for this.

.NET CORE INTERFACE IMPLEMENTATIONS

 * IDbContextFactory: This interface is responsible for creating DbContext
   instances.
 * IModelCustomizer: Modifies the model during EF Core bootstrapping.
 * IQueryProvider: Handles queries against custom data stores.

.NET STANDARD INTERFACE IMPLEMENTATIONS

 * IDbConnection: Establishes a connection to the data store.
 * IDbCommand: Represents a SQL command that can be executed.

